<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12116n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12116n">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12116n"> 116(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font><font color="green">[iustior]</font><font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> Canis suam Leo</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Votre science se d&eacute;robe derri&egrave;re l&apos;opinion de vos pr&eacute;decesseurs, de saint L&eacute;on en particulier. En une telle question, l&apos;humilit&eacute; qui s&apos;efface derri&egrave;re l&apos;opinion des d&eacute;funts, s&apos;expose &agrave; ne pas rencontrer la v&eacute;rit&eacute;.&rdquo; Et, empruntant &agrave; un vieux proverbe populaire un jeu de mots quelque peu d&eacute;plac&eacute;, il ajoutait: &ldquo;Dans le cas pr&eacute;sent, un chien vivant est plus utile qu&apos;un lion mort <font color="green">[n1: <i>Leo</i>, en latin, signifie &eacute;galement <i>lion</i> et <i>L&eacute;on</i>]</font>&rdquo;. <br><font color="green">[ &ldquo;[&hellip;]</font> Your science takes refuge behind the opinion of your predecessors, Saint Leon in particular. In such matters, the kind of humility that effaces itself behind the opinion of the deceased is liable never to reach the truth&rdquo;. And, borrowing a pun for an old proverb, he added: &ldquo;In the present case a living dog is more useful than a dead lion (n1)&rdquo;] <br>n1: <i>Leo</i>, en latin, signifie &eacute;galement <i>lion</i> et <i>L&eacute;on</i>. <br><font color="green">[n1: <i>Leo</i>, in Latin, signifies both lion and Leon]</font> <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 85</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Cf. Ecclesiastes 9.4: &ldquo;Il n&apos;y a personne qui vive toujours, ni qui ait m&ecirc;me cette esp&eacute;rance; un chien vivant vaut mieux qu&apos;un lion mort.&rdquo; (Vulgate: &ldquo;[&hellip;] melior est canis vivus leone mortuo&rdquo;).</mm> </dd></dl>
